ctions of both animal and human bodies before the king at Versailles and in front of hundreds of spectators at the King's Garden in Paris. At the Paris Academy of Sciences, meanwhile, Claude Perrault, with the help of Duverney’s dissections, edited two folios in the 1670s filled with lavish illustrations by court artists of exotic royal animals. Through the stories of Duverney and Perrault, as well as those of Marin Cureau de la Chambre, Jean Pecquet, and Louis Gayant, The Courtiers' Anatomists explores the relationships between empiricism and theory, human and animal, as well as the origins of the natural history museum and the relationship between science and other cultural activities, including art, music, and literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAnatomyxStudy and teachingzFrancezParisxHistory. 0aZoologyxStudy and teachingzFrancezParisxHistory. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  azoology, dead bodies, live animals, louis xiv, france, 17th-century anatomy, dissection, vivisection, insatiable curiosity, parisian scientists, monarchy, sun king, royal menageries, versailles, kings garden, paris academy of sciences, claude perrault, joseph-guichard duverney, lavish illustrations, court artists, exotic species, marin cureau de la chambre, jean pecquet, empiricism, theory, natural history museum, europe, society, culture, cultural activities.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022624766340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226248332423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226248332/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles